Let me put an anecdote in here at this point.
As dean of faculties, I took to Musgrave in 71 or 72.
I've forgotten which.
The provost from Columbia University had come to speak in what we called the Rudder Lectures.
These were to honor President Rudder's memory.
And he was going to give one of them at 8 o'clock April 21st.
muster was then held, I think, at 6 or 6.30.

After all, I've been to a lot of college campuses.
I said, sir, I don't think you really have been to anything like an Aggie muster.
It's rather distinctive.

was going but didn't want to go.
He thought he was doing a favor.

I mean, you heard the tone in some of their voices because for some I answered present in my heart because I'd had them in class.
As we walked out, he turned to me and he said, I understand this now.
